title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson M&P revolver
postcontent: If you are reading this, the gun is still available,  if you are interested,  please CALL or TEXT, I seldom check email.  My number is ( 269 ) 876-nine 7 six 2, I work days but can't always hear my phone so please leave a message if I don't answer and I will call or text back as soon as possible.  What I have is a 1940's Smith & Wesson M&P six shot revolver  that was part of the Lend Lease program used during and after World War II. It is one of the Victory models manufactured by S&W for the war effort. The gun was originally chambered in .38 Smith & Wesson,  but was converted to the .38 Special by Cogswell And Harrison of London, to be used by the British military and or police. This gun was returned to the US at the close of the Lend Lease program and is now up for sale. The serial numbers match the frame and crane however, the grips are not original to the gun ( very common considering the role of these guns ). The gun is in very good shape considering it's age and former life as a service weapon. It shoots very nice in single or double action with no problems at all. I am asking  $300 or best offer, the only reason I'm selling is to fund other projects so please don't send ridiculous offers, it was appraised at $400-450 in it's current condition.  Thank you for looking and again, no emails please.

title: For Sale:  380 Mark II Revolver ammo
postcontent:
Do you have a 380 Mark II Revolver and are having trouble locating ammo
I have 4 boxes with 12 rounds each of  CIS 380 2Z each
This ammo is for a 380 revolver that is no longer made and ammo is hard to find. 

Selling 36rds-$120.00 OBO


Info I found online-

Roundman :
CIS stands for Charter Industries of Singapore. The bullet is a 178 grain FMJ. I believe that the 2Z denotes the type of (flake) powder used.The green tin should have a sticker bearing the manufacture date , usually during the 1970's. The shell casings are difficult to reload. What appears to be a small pistol primer in the base of the shell is actually a non-standard primer. I don't remember the specs but it is not likely you will find replacement primers if you are considering reloading the empties. The ammo is often found in like new condition. The muzzle velocity is low - about 600 FPS. Large amounts of this ammo , along with the corresponding Webley .380 Mark 4 revolvers , were imported from the Singapore Police Force , in the period of about 1981-1991 , by various USA importers. It's hard to believe that this round was still in use by (foreign) police departments and military up until the 1980's. The round was used in the Webley and Enfield top-break revolvers. In fact , this ammo can be used in any 38 S&W (not Special) revolver.

title: For Sale:  Savage Model 93 Tactical w/ Accessories, AccuTrigger
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Savage Model 93 Tactical. The gun has a factory rough-textured tactical stock. The barrel is a fluted heavy bull barrel, and is fully-floated in the stock. It has a factory AccuTrigger worked down to 2.5lbs, with a very short pull and crisp break. It has an EGW 20 MOA picatinny scope base that has been fitted by a gunsmith to ensure it is true to the action, and a Harris S-BRM 6"-9" benchrest bipod w/swivel base. I have the original packaging for both the EGW scope base and the Harris bipod, as well as the original 2-piece scope bases that came on the gun. The gun will also include the original box, paperwork, .17 caliber bore snake, and AccuTrigger adjustment tool.

I'm also going to include 65 rounds of CCI 20-grain FMJ ammunition, which is by far the most accurate 17HMR ammo on the market. I bought 100 rounds for this gun, and only shot 35 rounds through it since new. The other 65 rounds are included with the gun. This gun in this configuration was designed as a long-range trainer to practice bullet drop and windage calculations, but I no longer have anywhere to shoot it. It is in perfect, like-new condition, and will easily shoot 1MOA groups with 20 grain ammunition. 17HMR is the most accurate rimfire caliber I've ever owned, and ammunition is easy to find at any gun store or Walmart (unlike .22lr). My asking price is significantly less than what I have invested, but I just don't have anywhere to shoot it anymore. Thanks for your interest, and please email with any questions. 
MSRP on this gun is $477, plus $110 for the bipod, and $50 for the scope base. I believe my asking price is fair considering this. I will consider serious trades or offers. Thanks again!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Les Baer Custom Carry 1911
postcontent:
This was my first 1911, and I believe it will be my last. It is an amazing gun, just not the direction I want to go.

Regular holster/presentation wear, a few nicks and scratches, but nothing that couldn't be refinished fairly easily by someone with the time or a blasting cabinet. I can provide a link to recent pics. I will gladly take more specific pics for anyone who asks.

This pistol has been flawless, no malfunctions whatsoever. I broke it in for roughly 2500 rounds, broke it down and replaced all the springs with a Wilson Bulletproof makeover kit. Maybe 250 rounds since. It has Novak type Tritium sights, only 2 years old, ambi safety, nicely beveled magwell, 25lpi hand checking on the frontstrap. I have a pair of ivory micarta grips on it right now, also have the LB cocobolo in a box here somewhere. It will come with the 2 LB 8rd mags, 3 CMC 8rd and 1 Tripp Research 8rd Cobra mag. I also have a couple holsters including a nice hybrid from HHH, a Milt Sparks VM2 and a Galco Miami Classic that could be added for the right deal.

I'm asking $1700 OBO

I'm in Terre Haute, and have to watch kids on the reg, so too long a drive would need some serious scheduling but isn't out of the question. 

 Feel free to make me an offer, the worst I'll say is no thanks. If you are serious about taking a look at the pistol or making a deal, let me know and I will provide cell contact info.

Thanks for looking!
